Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C. Take the @puff pastry sheet{1} out of your fridge. Remove and discard the root and green tops from the @leek{2}, halve lengthways and then thinly slice into thin half moon shapes. Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add the leek along with a pinch of @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Stir together and cook until really soft, ~{8-10%minutes}.

While the leek is cooking, grate the @lemon{1/2}(zested) and finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(finely chopped) (stalks and leaves!). Peel off the @hot smoked salmon{1}(skin removed). Pop the salmon in a #mixing bowl{} and separate the flakes with two #forks{}. Add the lemon zest, parsley, @wholegrain mustard{1%tbsp}, a pinch of salt and black pepper and stir together.

Once the leek is soft, add to the salmon mixture and mix together, then stir in the @crème fraîche{2%tbsp}. Taste the mixture (but don't eat it all!) and add more salt and black pepper if you feel it needs it. Unroll the pastry, halve widthways and lay on a piece of #baking paper{}.

Spoon the mixture onto one half of the pastry with a 2cm border around the edge. Dip your finger in water and run it around the edge of the pastry. Fold the other half of the pastry over so the two edges meet. Squeeze the edges together then use a #fork{} to seal them tightly. Use a #sharp knife{} to prick a small hole in the top of the pastry (this lets the steam escape).

Brush the pastry with @?milk{}, then sprinkle over half the @poppy seeds{1/2%tbsp}. Carefully transfer the baking paper and its contents to a #baking tray{}. Pop on the top shelf of your oven and bake until golden brown, ~{18-22%minutes}. Meanwhile, slice the @avocado{1}(chopped into 2cm chunks).

Squeeze the lemon juice into another mixing bowl and add the remaining @poppy seeds{1/2%tbsp}, the @honey{1%tbsp}, @olive oil{2%tbsp}, a pinch of salt and black pepper and mix together. Just before serving, add the avocado and @lamb's lettuce and bulls blood mix{} to the dressing and toss together. When the salmon en croûte is cooked, remove from your oven and carefully slice each one into two triangles. Serve with the salad on the side and enjoy!

> Here's our twist on a traditional showstopper. Salmon en croûte is a classic summer dish, guaranteed to wow party guests but even more decadent if you can keep it for yourself! Any leftovers would make a fabulous addition to a picnic. The buttery flesh in its zingy, lemony dressing is a perfect compliment.